1. **A plot of the accuracy every 30 steps, for each value of the regularization constant.**

This plot shows 300 steps across 50 epochs sampled every 30 steps. For a total of 500 data points (300/30)\*50. As you can see the lambda (regularization constant) of 0.001 performed the best overall and at the end.

This chart was evaluated using 50 training examples that were held out each epoch.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. **A plot of the magnitude of the coefficient vector every 30 steps, for each value of the regularization constant.**

This plot is like the first accuracy plot but instead it shows the magnitude of the coefficient vector over the 500 data points. As you can see as lambda becomes larger the magnitude of A (weights) become smaller because A has a growing impact on the cost function so the function tries to make A smaller.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. **Your estimate of the best value of the regularization constant, together with a brief description of why you believe that is a good value.**

This bar graph shows the accuracy of model trained on the training data and evaluated using the validation data which was not used for training. As you can see lambdas 0.001 and 0.0001 had the highest accuracy and any lower lambdas had no impact on improving the accuracy based off the validation data.

I believe the best value for lambda is 0.001 (orange) because it found the optimal position of the hyperplane (decision boundary) given the new unseen validation set. Furthermore, widening the margin of the decision boundary further by decreasing lambda to 0.0001 had no material effect on the validation data accuracy and could potentially misclassify test data.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)
